Compliance by Nigeria to crude oil output reduction set by the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), prompted a fall on the Cartel’s December overall production. OPEC’s largest production drop of 80,000 bpd was in Nigeria, which exported less crude according to ship-tracking data and loading schedules. Much of this decline came from reduced shipments of Bonga crude, which traders say has been undergoing maintenance.  According to Reuters survey, Nigeria and Iraq adhered more closely to pledged reductions and top exporter Saudi Arabia made further cuts ahead of a new production-limiting accord. On average, the 14-member of the Organisation pumped 29.50 million barrels per day (bpd) last month, according to the survey which is down 50,000 bpd from November’s revised figure. Crude prices have rallied to above $70 a barrel in 2020, extending a 23 per cent gain in 2019, supported by ongoing OPEC-led curbs and increased Middle East tensions after the killing of a top Iranian general. This has increased concern of conflict that could further cut supply. “Looking ahead, geopolitical risks will remain front and center of investor concerns,” said Stephen Brennock of oil broker PVM. “A tense waiting game has begun to see if the fallout will lead to a disruption in regional oil supplies.” The OPEC, Russia and other allies, known as OPEC+, had an agreement to reduce supply by 1.2 million bpd in 2019. OPEC’s share of the cut was about 800,000 bpd, to be made by 11 members, with exemptions for Iran, Libya and Venezuela. At meetings in December, OPEC+ agreed to make an additional cut of 500,000 bpd as of January 1, 2020. The 11 OPEC members bound by the agreement easily exceeded the pledged cuts, thanks in large part to Saudi Arabia and its Gulf allies cutting more than called for to support the market. The December survey suggests Nigeria and Iraq, both laggards in making cuts in 2019, achieved some progress. Compliance rose to 158 per cent in December, the survey found, from 153 per cent in November. OPEC’s two top producers, Saudi Arabia and Iraq, each reduced output by 50,000 bpd. This puts Saudi supply more than 500,000 bpd below its 2019 target. Iraq’s compliance, at 59 per cent, is far lower than Saudi Arabia’s but is up from 23% in November.